 Time Immemorial Through Rcap, the Trc, and Beyond -- tMoving to Action -- tEngaging Citizens in Indigenous–Non-Indigenous Relations -- tSshrc and the Conscientious Community: Reflecting and Acting on Indigenous Research and Reconciliation in Response to Cta 65 -- tCanada’s Aboriginal Policy and the Politics of Ambivalence: A Policy Tools Perspective -- tExecutive Summary: Canadian Public Opinion on Aboriginal Peoples -- tWhat’s the Way Forward? -- tThe Sharing the Land, Sharing a Future Forum Oversight Committee -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSharing the Land, Sharing a Future looks to both the past and the future as it examines the foundational work of the Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples (RCAP) and the legacy of its 1996 report. It assesses the Commission’s influence on subsequent milestones in Indigenous-Canada relations and considers our prospects for a constructive future. RCAP’s five-year examination of the relationships of First Nations, Metis, and Inuit peoples to Canada and to non-Indigenous Canadians resulted in a new vision for Canada and provided 440 specific recommendations, many of which informed the subsequent work of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Canada (TRC). Considered too radical and difficult to implement, RCAP’s recommendations were largely ignored, but the TRC reiterates that longstanding inequalities and imbalances in Canada’s relationship with Indigenous peoples remain and quite literally calls us to action. With reflections on RCAP’s legacy by its co-chairs, leaders of national Indigenous organizations and the Minister of Crown-Indigenous Relations, and leading academics and activists, this collection refocuses our attention on the groundbreaking work already performed by RCAP. Organized thematically, it explores avenues by which we may establish a new relationship, build healthy and powerful communities, engage citizens, and move to action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  aRCAP.  aTRC.  areconciliation.1 aAbele, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexiuk, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackstock, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBombay, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourassa, Carrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyer, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastellano, Marlene Brant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenis, Jeff S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewar, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiver, Sibyl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDockstator, Jennifer S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDockstator, Mark S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuhaime, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranks, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Katherine A.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Katherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerb George, Satsan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiller, Chr